&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;quot;you are an idiot~ ah, ah, ah, ah ...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;try &lt;code&gt;idiot.html&lt;/code&gt;. Oh, it&amp;apos;s Leopold. He says, &amp;quot;Now you should apologize...&amp;quot; and gives the link to the next level.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;OK, We have it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#level-20&#34; class=&#34;header-anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span id=&#34;level-20&#34;&gt;Level 20&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Well, I have no idea what to do. Again, I learned something during searching online.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img src=&#34;/img/ResponseHeaders.png&#34; alt=&#34;response headers&#34;&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The picture above are the response headers of &lt;code&gt;unreal.jpg&lt;/code&gt;. Now if we modify the &lt;code&gt;Range&lt;/code&gt; value in the request headers, we&amp;apos;ll get access to files of other range.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;apos;s clear that between 0 and 30202 bytes lies &lt;code&gt;unreal.jpg&lt;/code&gt;. Let&amp;apos;s go on to the next section. Set &lt;code&gt;Range&lt;/code&gt; value to &lt;code&gt;bytes=30203-&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
